    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided filing excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of the Connectivity segment\'s maturity, Starlink\'s profitability, and capital expenditure trends:\n\n### 1. Connectivity Segment Maturity\nThe filing portrays the Connectivity segment as a highly mature, scaled, and profitable business, especially when contrasted with the "early-stage" and heavily loss-making AI segment. \n* **Sustained Profitability:** The segment became "Segment Adjusted EBITDA positive on a sustained basis beginning in 2023."\n* **Revenue Quality:** It generates "predictable and recurring revenue" from a diversified base of consumer, enterprise, and government customers.\n* **Operational Scale:** The company notes that strong sequential EBITDA growth has been driven by "expanding the scale and efficiency of our LEO [Low-Earth Orbit] satellite constellations and our highly verticalized supply [chain]."\n* **Strategic Role:** Alongside the Space segment, Connectivity is viewed as a proven engine of value creation that is now helping to fund the company\'s aggressive expansion into AI.\n\n### 2. Starlink Profitability\nStarlink is the primary driver of the Connectivity segment and exhibits strong, rapidly growing profitability, though it is navigating shifting unit economics due to global expansion.\n* **Financial Performance (2025 Full Year):** The segment generated **$11.39 billion** in revenue, **$4.42 billion** in operating income, and **$7.17 billion** in Adjusted EBITDA. This represents massive year-over-year growth of 49.8%, 120.4%, and 86.2%, respectively.\n* **Financial Performance (Q1 2026):** Revenue reached **$3.26 billion**, with operating income of **$1.19 billion** and Adjusted EBITDA of **$2.09 billion**.\n* **Growth Drivers vs. Headwinds:** \n  * **Volume over ARPU:** Profitability is being fueled by massive user adoption. In Q1 2026, Starlink Subscribers grew by **104.7%** (reaching 10.3 million subscribers). However, this was offset by a **22.9% decline in ARPU** (down to $66/month), which the company attributes to international expansion and the introduction of lower-priced service plans.\n  * **Enterprise Adoption:** Growth is further bolstered by increasing enterprise and government sales, particularly in aviation, maritime, and mobility.\n  * **Rising Costs:** Profit margins are being partially offset by higher depreciation expenses (due to increased satellite launch cadences), ground operating costs, and international expansion/marketing costs. \n\n### 3. Capital Expenditure (CapEx) Trends\nThe filing reveals a massive, accelerating CapEx cycle across all three segments, with total capital expenditures nearly quintupling from 2023 to 2025. Total CapEx grew from **$4.4 billion in 2023** to **$11.2 billion in 2024**, and reached **$20.7 billion in 2025**. In Q1 2026 alone, the company spent **$10.1 billion**.\n\n* **AI Segment (The Dominant Driver):** AI CapEx has exploded to capture a "$26.5 trillion potential market opportunity." It grew from $463 million in 2023 to $5.6 billion in 2024, and **$12.7 billion in 2025**. In Q1 2026, AI CapEx was **$7.7 billion**, driven by massive investments in compute infrastructure, GPU hardware, data center expansions, and power generation. The company expects a "multi-year investment horizon" before AI generates sustained positive EBITDA.\n* **Connectivity Segment (Steady Expansion):** CapEx continues to scale to support the LEO constellation and ground infrastructure. It grew from $2.5 billion in 2023 to $3.5 billion in 2024, and **$4.2 billion in 2025**. Q1 2026 CapEx was **$1.3 billion**.\n* **Space Segment (Starship Focus):** CapEx has roughly doubled year-over-year, rising from $1.5 billion in 2023 to $2.0 billion in 2024, and **$3.8 billion in 2025**. Q1 2026 CapEx was **$1.1 billion**. This increase is primarily driven by accelerated investments in next-generation Starship vehicle production and launch site infrastructure. \n\n**Summary:** The filing illustrates a company using the mature, highly profitable cash flows of its Connectivity/Starlink business to help fund an aggressive, capital-intensive build-out of AI compute infrastructure and next-generation Space (Starship) capabilities.',
